@Sam Lyons

One of the many convenient things about Lucek the Poodle is how he lets us lie in. I usually wake up before my wife. Jorge the Lab was always at my bedside as soon as I stirred. Actually, even a bit before that - he had a sixth sense when it came to identifying the exact moment my body decided it was no longer going to let me sleep. He pawed at me and poked me with his nose: c'mon, get up, let's walk, let's eat, let's do stuff!!! And I could never say "no" to him.

Lucek though, he will wait patiently until I decide to get up. It's so weird!

@Andrzej
When The Dog was alive—and before El Señor showed up in our lives—we had it good on weekends. The Dog would sleep in as long as we let her. Around noon or so, I’d finally make her go outside because, hello, excessive bladder pressure. She’d stop on the porch. “Go, go pee.” Nope. “I’d go down the steps with her.” “Come ON.” Still nope. I’d venture—barefoot—all the way to the driveway. “Go pee for chrissakes!” She’d sniff the air, stretch, maybe plop down on her butt. I’d have to flap my arms like a chicken, or cross the driveway with her into the trees (so much fun barefoot when you’re among pine trees), or even sometimes go back inside and enlist my husband’s help before she’d deign to empty her bladder. One time, I’d left my car in the driveway, and she actually went behind it, stood there for a minute, and then came prancing back with her “I peed! I peed!” dance. No, no you didn’t, I could see your legs just past the undercarriage the whole time, you oddest—and apparently most dishonest—of dogs. 

And now we have a cat who starts his Sun Salutation vinyasa flow the moment it gets light out—which in summer is at ungodly hours up here around the 60th parallel north.

