@Ms. Billie M. Spaight
I cannot conceive of how saying "falling on deaf ears" could possibly hurt actual deaf people. Or "turn a blind eye," or "lame duck," or any other such metaphor.

Getting upset over little things like this distracts from the real discrimination that people with disabilities face. Every time you police someone's language for perceived slights you are making it that much more difficult for disabled people to get respect.

@Ms. Billie M. Spaight
I feel sorry, reading your comment, that you are finding these "old sayings" hurtful.  People should not be so quick to disparage your feelings, which I am sure you come by honestly. 

   I  try to focus a little more, instead, on "people-first language."  PhysicsDaughter just rode in a horse show that featured events for "Disabled Riders."  It wouldn't take that much ink and space to use "Riders with Disabilities"... which would be more accurate:  the fact is, of course, that once on her horse, she is NOT so disabled.

